                     <interp inst="t18301028-186-off1036" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18301028-186-cd1037" type="crimeDate">27th of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-186-off1036 t18301028-186-cd1037"></join>, 3 pecks of coals, value 1s. 3d., the goods of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18301028-186-victim1591" type="victimName">
                           Press 
                           Granger
                        <interp inst="t18301028-186-victim1591" type="surname" value="Granger"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18301028-186-victim1591" type="given" value="Press"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18301028-186-victim1591" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-186-off1036 t18301028-186-victim1591"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , from a wharf adjacent to the navigable river Thames
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>GEORGE HUGHES. I am a waterman and lighterman. Press Granger's wharf is at <placeName id="t18301028-186-crimeloc1038">St. Ann's, Limehouse</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-186-crimeloc1038" type="placeName" value="St. Ann's, Limehouse"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-186-crimeloc1038" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-186-off1036 t18301028-186-crimeloc1038"></join>; I was there on the 27th of September, at seven o'clock in the evening, and saw the prisoner on the wharf, putting coals into a bag - he scratched them in with his hands; I went and told the clerk - he came, unlocked the gate, and charged the prisoner with stealing the coals; there were<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183010280083"></xptr>about three pecks in the bag - as soon as the prisoner got off the premises he began to abuse me - he struck me, and gave me a black eye; he struck the clerk, and had a long struggle with him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Where were you? A. I was attending a barge about twenty yards from the premises.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301028-186-person1592">
                  JOHN 
                  HUNTER
               <interp inst="t18301028-186-person1592" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301028-186-person1592" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301028-186-person1592" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-officer, and took the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301028-186-person1593">
                  JOSEPH 
                  JAMES
               <interp inst="t18301028-186-person1593" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301028-186-person1593" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301028-186-person1593" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a clerk on the wharf. The gates were locked; the prisoner had no authority to be there - I do not know how he got there; he struck me several times very severely - the coals were Mr. Granger's.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. When you first came, did you not make a kick at me? A. No; I said I had caught you at last - your bag was alongside of you.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been working on the adjoining premises; I had occasion to go on these premises, and was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18301028-186-verdict1039" type="verdictDescription">
